      <hedline>
        <hl1>Case Goes to New York F.B.I. Office</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Federal Bureau of Investigation assigns its New York office to lead investigation into terrorist attack against US destroyer Cole in Yemen (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>The Federal Bureau of Investigation has assigned its New York office to lead the investigation of the Yemen bombing, a law enforcement official said yesterday.</p>
        <p>That means that any prosecution that might ultimately result from the Yemen investigation would be brought by the office of Mary Jo White, the United States attorney in Manhattan, whose prosecutors have vast experience in terrorism cases, most recently in the investigation of the Saudi exile Osama bin Laden.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>The Federal Bureau of Investigation has assigned its New York office to lead the investigation of the Yemen bombing, a law enforcement official said yesterday.</p>
        <p>That means that any prosecution that might ultimately result from the Yemen investigation would be brought by the office of Mary Jo White, the United States attorney in Manhattan, whose prosecutors have vast experience in terrorism cases, most recently in the investigation of the Saudi exile Osama bin Laden.</p>
        <p>Ms. White's office declined comment.</p>
        <p>The authorities suspect him of masterminding the 1998 attacks on the American Embassies in Kenya and Tanzania, which killed more than 200 people and wounded thousands, and of a number of other acts of terror that have taken place against Americans abroad.</p>
        <p>The decision suggests that the government is intent on pursuing the Yemen bombing as a crimnal case and that the authorities have not ruled out a link to some terrorist groups that in the past have been the focus of scrutiny by the federal investigators in New York, including Mr. bin Laden and his group.</p>
      </block>
